author: Al Jazeera English
description:
In Madagascar, soldiers from a key army corps have declared solidarity with protesters, urging police to disregard government orders. Demonstrations let by so-called Gen Z youths have been protesting for weeks, growing from anger over power and water outages into a wider movement opposing the government. The United Nations says at least 22 people have been killed in the unrest; the government disputes that figure. The president has dissolved his cabinet and appointed a new prime minister, but protesters say that’s not enough.

Al Jazeera’s Ali Hashem reports.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Steve Witkoff, Trump’s special envoy to the Middle East, has been speaking to thousands of people at a rally in Tel Aviv in support of the Israeli captives set to be released from Gaza. Flanked by Trump’s daughter Ivanka and her husband, Jared Kushner, Witkoff was met with cheers of “Thank you!” but he was interrupted with boos several times when he mentioned Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu. “I was in the trenches with the prime minister. Believe me, he was a very important part here,” Witkoff told the crowd. Relatives of the Israeli captives have accused Netanyahu of blocking efforts to secure the release of their loved-ones and end the Gaza war for his own political gain. But Witkoff said Netanyahu and his chief negotiator, Ron Dermer, “have both sacrificed so much for this country and devoted their lives to the service of Israel”.

title: Trump’s Middle East envoy hails Netanyahu at Tel Aviv rally, drawing boos

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Tens of thousands of Palestinians are streaming back to their land in northern Gaza—a right of return included in the ceasefire deal between Hamas and Israel. Multiple attempts to remove the population have failed. Many Palestinians say they have avoided another Nakba—or catastrophe—and defeated Israel's forced displacement policy. But the land they are returning to is unrecognisable. Is Gaza uninhabitable? Or can it be rebuilt under the interim authority that next governs the strip? And does the ceasefire allow for this complex and lengthy task?  

Presenter: Imran Khan 
Guests:
Ines Abdel Razek -- Co-director of the Palestine Institute for Public Diplomacy
Ilan Pappe -- Chairman of the Nakba Memorial Foundation
Ghada Karmi -- Academic and the author of ‘Return: A Palestinian Memoir’

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Amid reports that Israel does not want Turkish forces to be involved in any stabilisation force for Gaza, Yusuf Alabarda, a former NATO officer, notes that Israel has a say only on what happens within its own internationally recognised borders. “For this reason, I do believe that the Turkish forces will be inside the Gaza Strip,” Alabarda told Al Jazeera from Ankara, the Turkish capital. He explained that Turkiye has vast experience in conflict areas, as well as technical expertise in reconstruction. For example, the Turkish government has responded to earthquakes that have caused widespread damage.“Two years ago, there was a huge earthquake inside Turkiye, and there were temporarily built barracks that Turkiye offered to the victims of the earthquake. They are available now for [use in] Gaza,” Alabarda said.

Cameroon heads to the polls in what many see as a defining moment for one of Africa’s oldest leaders and one of the continent’s youngest electorates. Nearly three-quarters of the population are under 35. The 92-year-old incumbent, Paul Biya, is running again after more than 40 years in power. He says his next term would focus on improving the lives of women and young people. Other contenders include Bello Bouba Maigari. He's the leader of the National Union for Democracy and Progress, which was once allied with Biya’s governing party.

Al Jazeera’s Ahmed Idris reports from Yaounde.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
This decisive decade demands unprecedented action to address humanity’s greatest challenge. With global access, this three-part series examines the real consequences of climate change for our civilisation, through the rest of the 21st century and beyond.

Irish journalist Philip Boucher-Hayes visits climate hotspots, from Greenland’s melting glaciers to sub-Saharan Africa’s weather extremes, from the flooding of agricultural land in Bangladesh to the thaw of the Siberian permafrost. He meets experts and witnesses who explain the interconnectivity of the world’s fragile ecology, as we reach tipping points from which there may be no return.

The series looks at new climate science and faces the harsh realities of a changing world - collapsing ecosystems, marine die-offs and escalating extreme weather phenomena. description:
Following the ceasefire, families from southern Gaza return to Gaza City only to find their homes completely destroyed. One displaced family is now living in the remains of a house they do not own — without running water, electricity, or sanitation — facing harsh conditions and a constant fear that the war could resume.

This story highlights the daily struggle of Gazans returning to ruins, as winter approaches and no lasting solutions are in sight. Despite everything, the will to endure and stay on their land remains strong, as people cling to both survival and memory.

Al Jazeera’s Ibrahim Al Khalili reports.
